(
<figureCitation id="132F2A6BC963FFD47E9BFA341EBD1674" box="[159,244,1516,1542]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="30.[151,255,1528,1552]" captionTargetBox="[194,1391,181,1512]" captionTargetId="figure-162@30.[168,1418,172,1547]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURE 10. SEM micrographs of chaetae in Bathyvermilia kupriyanovae. USA, off California, 34°41' N, 123°08' W, 4100 m, legit K.L. Smith, R/V New Horizon, det. H.A. ten Hove, Natural History Museum of LA County, USA. A—details of Apomatus chaetae of 4th thoracic chaetiger, B—uncini of 4th thoracic chaetiger, C—posterior abdominal uncini, D—detail of middle abdominal chaeta." pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
)
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BAB36EEC963FFD47E93F9E01D051621" blockId="28.[151,844,1592,1658]" box="[151,844,1592,1619]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
<emphasis id="B960EAFCC963FFD47E93F9E01F7D1620" bold="true" box="[151,308,1592,1618]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Type-species</emphasis>
: 
<taxonomicName id="4C144D6DC963FFD47F40F9E11D051621" authority="Zibrowius, 1973 a" authorityName="Zibrowius" authorityYear="1973" box="[324,844,1593,1619]" class="Polychaeta" family="Serpulidae" genus="Bathyvermilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="challengeri">
<emphasis id="B960EAFCC963FFD47F40F9E11C3F1620" box="[324,630,1593,1618]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Bathyvermilia challengeri</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EF854B1FC963FFD47C7AF9E11D051621" author="Zibrowius, H." box="[638,844,1593,1619]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="427 - 439" refId="ref69786" refString="Zibrowius, H. (1973 a) Revision of some Serpulidae (Annelida Polychaeta) from abyssal depths in the Atlantic and Pacific, collected by the &quot; Challenger &quot; and Prince of Monaco Expeditions. Bulletin of British Museum of Natural History (Zoology), 24, 427 - 439." type="journal article" year="1973">Zibrowius, 1973a</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BAB36EEC963FFD47E93F9B81FD11608" blockId="28.[151,844,1592,1658]" box="[151,408,1632,1658]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Number of species: 5.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BAB36EEC963FFD57E93F9751C261154" blockId="28.[151,1436,1709,2009]" lastBlockId="29.[151,1436,152,294]" lastPageId="29" lastPageNumber="30" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
Tube white, opaque, circular in cross-section, longitudinal keel may be present. Collar-like rings present. Granular overlay absent. Operculum sub-globular, with simple flat to slightly conical chitinous endplate, which may be encrusted by calcareous deposit. Peduncle cylindrical, smooth or wrinkled, without distal wings; inserted as second dorsal radiole on one side, constriction present. Pseudoperculum absent. Arrangement of radioles in semi-circles, up to 35 per lobe. Inter-radiolar membrane absent. Branchial eyes not observed. Stylodes absent. Mouth palps may be present. 7 thoracic chaetigerous segments. Collar trilobed (may be non-lobed) with entire edge, tonguelets absent. Thoracic membranes variable, ending at 2 
<superScript id="7C619BA6C963FFD47B57F84D1B2A17D1" attach="none" box="[1363,1379,1941,1955]" fontSize="6" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">nd</superScript>
—7 
<superScript id="7C619BA6C963FFD47B8BF84D1BD217D1" attach="none" box="[1423,1435,1941,1955]" fontSize="6" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">th</superScript>
thoracic segment. Collar chaetae limbate. 
<taxonomicName id="4C144D6DC963FFD47C8DF8671CB717AA" authorityName="Philippi" authorityYear="1844" box="[649,766,1983,2008]" class="Polychaeta" family="Serpulidae" genus="Apomatus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B960EAFCC963FFD47C8DF8671CB717AA" box="[649,766,1983,2008]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Apomatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
chaetae present (
<figureCitation id="132F2A6BC963FFD47DC9F8671A7217AB" box="[973,1083,1983,2009]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="30.[151,255,1528,1552]" captionTargetBox="[194,1391,181,1512]" captionTargetId="figure-162@30.[168,1418,172,1547]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURE 10. SEM micrographs of chaetae in Bathyvermilia kupriyanovae. USA, off California, 34°41' N, 123°08' W, 4100 m, legit K.L. Smith, R/V New Horizon, det. H.A. ten Hove, Natural History Museum of LA County, USA. A—details of Apomatus chaetae of 4th thoracic chaetiger, B—uncini of 4th thoracic chaetiger, C—posterior abdominal uncini, D—detail of middle abdominal chaeta." pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Fig. 10A</figureCitation>
). Thoracic uncini saw-shaped (
<figureCitation id="132F2A6BC962FFD57E9BFF401F4310C0" box="[159,266,152,178]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="30.[151,255,1528,1552]" captionTargetBox="[194,1391,181,1512]" captionTargetId="figure-162@30.[168,1418,172,1547]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURE 10. SEM micrographs of chaetae in Bathyvermilia kupriyanovae. USA, off California, 34°41' N, 123°08' W, 4100 m, legit K.L. Smith, R/V New Horizon, det. H.A. ten Hove, Natural History Museum of LA County, USA. A—details of Apomatus chaetae of 4th thoracic chaetiger, B—uncini of 4th thoracic chaetiger, C—posterior abdominal uncini, D—detail of middle abdominal chaeta." pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Fig. 10B</figureCitation>
), with few teeth (6 to 10). Anterior fang simple, pointed. Abdominal chaetae flat, narrow geniculate with blunt teeth (
<figureCitation id="132F2A6BC962FFD57F65FF661F8610AA" box="[353,463,190,216]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="30.[151,255,1528,1552]" captionTargetBox="[194,1391,181,1512]" captionTargetId="figure-162@30.[168,1418,172,1547]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURE 10. SEM micrographs of chaetae in Bathyvermilia kupriyanovae. USA, off California, 34°41' N, 123°08' W, 4100 m, legit K.L. Smith, R/V New Horizon, det. H.A. ten Hove, Natural History Museum of LA County, USA. A—details of Apomatus chaetae of 4th thoracic chaetiger, B—uncini of 4th thoracic chaetiger, C—posterior abdominal uncini, D—detail of middle abdominal chaeta." pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Fig. 10D</figureCitation>
); abdominal uncini saw-shaped, except in a few far posterior segments, with raspshaped uncini (
<figureCitation id="132F2A6BC962FFD57F53FF3D1F83108D" box="[343,458,229,255]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="30.[151,255,1528,1552]" captionTargetBox="[194,1391,181,1512]" captionTargetId="figure-162@30.[168,1418,172,1547]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURE 10. SEM micrographs of chaetae in Bathyvermilia kupriyanovae. USA, off California, 34°41' N, 123°08' W, 4100 m, legit K.L. Smith, R/V New Horizon, det. H.A. ten Hove, Natural History Museum of LA County, USA. A—details of Apomatus chaetae of 4th thoracic chaetiger, B—uncini of 4th thoracic chaetiger, C—posterior abdominal uncini, D—detail of middle abdominal chaeta." pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Fig. 10C</figureCitation>
). Short achaetous anterior abdominal zone present. Posterior capillary chaetae present. Posterior glandular pad present.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
